    "summary": "A new policy paper warns that Somalia's security operations could grind to a halt by year-end unless the UN Support Office in Somalia (UNSOS) mandate is renewed. The U.S. decision to withhold support for the mission threatens to reverse two decades of peacebuilding gains.",
    "content": "Somalia is approaching a critical juncture in its security transition, with the United Nations Support Office in Somalia (UNSOS) mandate set to expire at the end of 2025. A policy paper released by Balqiis Insights, titled “No Time To Drift: Somalia and the Deadline for a Managed Security Transition,” warns that without an extension, the country could face “operational paralysis.” The paper highlights that the U.S. government, as of July 1, 2026, has decided not to support the renewal of UNSOS, which provides logistical and administrative backing to Somali security forces and the African Union Transition Mission in Somalia (ATMIS).\n\nThe potential lapse in international support comes as Somali forces continue to battle Al-Shabaab militants. The United Nations has been a key backer of security sector reform in Somalia since the early 2000s, aiding in the establishment of a functional national army and police force. Analysts fear that the withdrawal of UNSOS could leave Somali troops without essential supplies, fuel, and medical support, undermining recent military gains against insurgents.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, the security situation in their homeland remains a pressing concern. Many diaspora members have contributed remittances and investments to support rebuilding efforts, and a resurgence of instability could disrupt these flows. Additionally, the potential for increased violence may lead to further displacement, affecting family members still in the country. The diaspora also plays a role in advocating for continued international engagement, making the UNSOS deadline a topic of interest for community organizations abroad.\n\nThe Balqiis paper calls for a managed transition, urging Somali authorities and international partners to develop a realistic plan that avoids a sudden gap in support. Without such measures, the country could slide back into the chaos that characterized the early 2000s, erasing hard-won progress in governance and security.\n\nRead the original report from Somalia Guardian here: https://www.somaliguardian.com/news/somalia-news/somalia-security-crisis-un-support-deadline-2026/",
    "source": "somaliguardian.com",
    "source_name": "Somalia Guardian",
